message.content:
The Catholic Church is typically associated with a few main symbols, some of which include:

1. The Crucifix: This is the most recognizable symbol of Christianity and represents Jesus' sacrifice on the cross for humanity’s sins.

2. The Ichthys (Fish): Often referred to as "the sign of the fish," it was used by early Christians as a secret symbol representing their faith. It also creates an acronym that translates to "Jesus Christ, God's Son, Savior."

3. Alpha and Omega: These are the first and last letters of the Greek alphabet and signify that God is eternal – he has no beginning or end.

4. Chi-Rho: Formed by superimposing the first two letters (XP) of Christ in Greek (Χριστός), this monogram represents Jesus Christ.

5. Sacred Heart: Depicting a flaming heart encircled by thorns or wrapped around a crown, this symbolizes Jesus' love for humanity through his suffering.

6. Dove: Representing peace and purity, doves are often depicted in Christian works as carrying an olive branch as well – bearing additional biblical significance due to Noah's story from Genesis.

7. Lamb: Symbolizing innocence, lambs have come to represent Jesus (the "Lamb of God") who was sacrificed for human salvation.

8. Bread & Wine/Cup & Host: In reference to Communion during Mass - where bread becomes the Body of Christ - this imagery often appears alongside other Eucharistic elements like cups/grails containing wine transformed into His blood during consecration rites within Catholic liturgies worldwide today!
